TypeScript is a statically typed superset of JavaScript that adds type annotations and type checking to the language. When used with React, TypeScript can help catch errors early in the development process and make code more readable and maintainable. In this article, we’ll explore how to use TypeScript with React by creating a simple component that displays a greeting message.

## Setting up the project

To get started, we’ll need to create a new React project and install the necessary dependencies. We can use `create-react-app` to create a new project and then install TypeScript and the necessary TypeScript typings for React:

```
npx create-react-app my-app --template typescript
cd my-app
npm install @types/react @types/react-dom
```

This will create a new React project with TypeScript already set up. We can now start creating our components.

## Creating a component

Let’s create a simple component that displays a greeting message. We’ll start by creating a new file called `Greeting.tsx` in the `src` directory:

```tsx
import React from 'react';

interface Props {
  name: string;
}

const Greeting: React.FC<Props> = ({ name }) => {
  return <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>;
};

export default Greeting;
```

In this file, we’ve defined a new component called `Greeting`. The component takes a single prop called `name`, which is a string. We’ve defined an interface called `Props` to describe the shape of the props object that the component expects.

The component itself is a functional component that takes the `name` prop as an argument and returns a JSX element that displays a greeting message. We’ve used the `React.FC` type to specify that this is a functional component that takes props as an argument and returns a JSX element.

Finally, we’ve exported the `Greeting` component so that it can be used in other files.

## Using the component

Now that we’ve created our `Greeting` component, we can use it in other files by importing it and rendering it as a JSX element. Let’s create a new file called `App.tsx` in the `src` directory:

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import Greeting from './Greeting';

const App: React.FC = () => {
  return (
    <div>
      <Greeting name="World" />
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In this file, we’ve imported the `Greeting` component and rendered it as a JSX element inside the `App` component. We’ve passed the `name` prop to the `Greeting` component and set it to `"World"`.

## Conclusion

In this article, we’ve explored how to use TypeScript with React by creating a simple component that displays a greeting message. We’ve seen how to define props using interfaces, how to create functional components using the `React.FC` type, and how to use components in other files by importing them and rendering them as JSX elements. By using TypeScript with React, we can catch errors early in the development process and make our code more readable and maintainable.

