To create a Chrome Extension that allows users to watch a video at the same time using JW Player, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a new folder for your extension and initialize a new npm project:

```
mkdir my-extension
cd my-extension
npm init -y
```

2. Create a `manifest.json` file in the root directory with the following content:

```json
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "JW Player Watch Party",
  "version": "1.0",
  "description": "Create a shared watch party using JW Player",
  "permissions": [
    "activeTab",
    "storage",
    "http://*/*",
    "https://*/*"
  ],
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"],
    "persistent": false
  },
  "content_scripts": [
    {
      "matches": ["https://*/*"],
      "js": ["content.js"]
    }
  ],
  "browser_action": {
    "default_popup": "popup.html",
    "default_icon": {
      "16": "images/icon16.png",
      "48": "images/icon48.png",
      "128": "images/icon128.png"
    }
  },
  "icons": {
    "16": "images/icon16.png",
    "48": "images/icon48.png",
    "128": "images/icon128.png"
  }
}
```

3. Create a `background.js` file in the root directory with the following content:

```javascript
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener(function(request, sender, sendResponse) {
  if (request.action === "pauseVideo") {
    chrome.tabs.query({active: true, currentWindow: true}, function(tabs) {
      chrome.tabs.sendMessage(tabs[0].id, {action: "pauseVideo"});
    });
  }
});
```

4. Create a `content.js` file in the root directory with the following content:

```javascript
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function() {
  var jwPlayer = document.querySelector(".jw-video");

  if (jwPlayer) {
    jwPlayer.addEventListener("pause", function() {
      chrome.runtime.sendMessage({action: "pauseVideo"});
    });
  }
});
```

5. Create a `popup.html` file in the root directory with the following content:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>JW Player Watch Party</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <button id="pauseButton">Pause Video</button>
    <script src="popup.js"></script>
  </body>
</html>
```

6. Create a `popup.js` file in the root directory with the following content:

```javascript
document.getElementById("pauseButton").addEventListener("click", function() {
  chrome.runtime.sendMessage({action: "pauseVideo"});
});
```

7. Create a `images` folder in the root directory and add the following images:

- `icon16.png` (16x16)
- `icon48.png` (48x48)
- `icon128.png` (128x128)

8. Create a `styles.css` file in the root directory with the following content:

```css
body {
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

button {
  background-color: #4CAF50;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

button:hover {
  background-color: #45a049;
}
```

9. Install the JW Player extension on your Chrome browser.

10. Load the extension by visiting `chrome://extensions/` and enabling "Developer mode".

11. Click "Load unpacked" and select the `my-extension` folder.

12. Visit a webpage that uses JW Player, such as YouTube or Vimeo.

13. Click the Chrome Extension icon to open the popup window.

14. Click the "Pause Video" button to pause the video.

15. All users who have the extension installed will see the video paused.

16. To resume the video, click the "Pause Video" button again.

Note: This extension assumes that the JW Player video is embedded on the webpage using the standard JW Player embed code. If the video is not embedded using JW Player, you will need to modify the extension to work with the specific video player.

